{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_clare_ver03/data/sn97063233/00414188023/1945101801/0047.xml":{"full_text":"THE WYANDOTTE NEWS HERALD\nPAGE FOUR\nVictory Garden\nFall Plowing\nBegins November 1\nPall plowing for next year's Vic\ntory Gardens will begin November\n3. Superintendent of Parts. Howard\n8010, has announced.\nGardeners are reminded that late\ncrop of carrots, cabbage and similar\nvegetables should be harvested be\nfore that date and the ground pre\npared for plowing. Those who plan\non a garden for next summer\nshould make application at once for\nplowing service if they have not\nalready done so.\nNOW IT IS FALL\ni'ivmiv ct imk\nPUBLIC NOTICE |9H\nI To Resident* Ipjl\n1 Wyandotte r8 V IBR\n1 Now Being P\u00bb\u2019\u00ab d IP\nI TREE planting\nI when >-\u2122y d U^ou h wiUl\nI been P ave Wanted be- 1\n1 want trees walk and 1\ntween the c r them 1\nI roadway- planting\nnow for later v that I\nI w f n S t h g e 6 various!\n1 re f' d blocks get together 1\n1 b j\u201erthe:r trees as 1\nI and order the wiU be I\nI a gr Mo P rab7e saving thisl\nconsiderable ne u j 1\nI Va J a representative will\n1 j\nGarden\n111\n*\"A If\n\nA GIFT FOR YOU... /A\nPocket-size Reduction of Your l H I\nDischarge Papers in a I\nPlastic Case Jjf\nVets Bring your discharge papers in\nhave them reproduced in miniature\nabsolutely without charge.\nYea, Sir you will have them back\n(both miniature and original)\nin just a few days.\nThis reproduction, complete in a plastic\ncase is yours for the asking! j|\n[riPPKI MONDAY THRU THURSDAY TO 6 P.M.\nvrtn FRIDAY AND SATURDAY TO 9 P.M.J\nCHELSEA CLOTHES f\nSMART STYLES FOR MEN ALWAYS\n3026 FIRST STREET J\nTHURSDAY, OCTOBER 18. 1945\n\"Those who delay making appli\ncation risk disappointment,\u201d said\nSolo. \"We have a limited amount of\nequipment and for this reason it\nIs highly important that as much\nox' the plowing as possible be done\nthis Fall,\u201d he continued.\nApplications for garden plots and\nplowing service are being received\nat the office of the mayor in the\nCity Hall, phone 2080.\nThe War Advertising Council re\nported that American Business dur\ning 1944 contributed $302,248,775\nworth of its own advertising to sup\nport government and home front\ninformation campaigns. This figure\nrepresented a 8% increase over the\nvolume of 1943.\nEVERGREENS\nSHRUBBERY\nTREES PLANTS\nJust Arrived! Pre-War\nHOLLAND\nALL FIRST QUALITY!\n2934 FORT. cor. Progress\nw -Mm LINCOLN PARK 7 Blocks\nMW South of Southfield Rd.\nPhone ATlanlic 5055\nBrothers Meet In Philippines\nPfc. Mitchell J. Seborowski re- j\ncently met his two brothers in the\nPhilippine islands. Pfc. Seborowski,\nwhose home is at 3533 Twelfth\nstreet, flew to Manila from Leyte\nisland where he is stationed to see\nhis brother, Sgt. Chet Seborowski.\nHis other brother, Raymond, Fl/c,\nUSN, stationed in Samau, visited\nhim in Leyte.\nThe Wyandotte serviceman also\nwrote of meeting Pfc. Nick Laritz,\nof 3532 Sixteenth street and Joe\nPivovar, S. C. 3-c of 248 Orange\nstreet.\nHis address is: Pfc. Mitchell J. j\nSeborowski, 36473948, Btry. C. 428\nArmored F. A. Bn., APO 932. c-o\nPostmaster, San Francisco, Calif.\nBuy Victory Bonds\nState President\nto Speak Here\ni. f.\nRobert M. Reames\nRobert M. Reames of Jackson,\nstate president of the Michigan\nJunior Chamber of Commerce, will\nbe the speaker at the opening din\nner meeting of the season for the\nWyandotte Jaycees.\nSixty members and guests are\nexpected next Monday evening at\nthe Wabeel? tea room to hear Mr.\ni Reames speak on \u201cThe Future and\nIts Challenge.\u201d\nReames is a past president of the\nLansing Jaycees and was state\ntreasurer and vice-president prior\nto assuming his present office.\nPainting, by Loral\nArtist Now on\nExhibition Here\n\u201cThe Valley Church,\u201d an original\noil painting by Charles E. S. Eddie,\nprominent local artist, is now' on\nexhibition at the Lynch and Sulli\nvan show window' at 2955 Biddle.\nThe painting was especially\ncreated for the YMCA building by\nMr. Eddie and will be on display\nfor another week before it is hung\non the wall of the large main floor\nroom of the YMCA building.\nWith a realistic sky background,\nthe painting shows a peaceful com\nmunity with a road winding its\nway through the trees to the little\ntown church. In the rear fore\nground the tall towering steeple\nof the church is pictured against\nthe sky. Mr. Eddie has completed\nI numerous paintings and has done\nconsiderable sculpture work. He is\na member of the Acanthus club\n1 and has exhibited at the annual\nart show of the group. He studied\nwith Anthony Themic, Rockport,\nMass. One of his sculpture pieces\nwas accepted by the Michigan Art\ni ists group and is now a part of the\ngroup's exhibition at the Detroit\nArt Institute.\nThirty-one correspondents and\nphotographers were killed during the\nwar. Twenty-nine were wounded,\nwhile five were captured by the\nenemy.\nTROOP WY 3\nBoy Scout troop Wy-3 left Fri\nday evening for a two-day \u201cKlon\ndike\u201d camping trip at Camp How\nell, Brighton, Michigan. The boys\nwere in charge of Assistant Scout\nmaster, \u201cRed\u201d Friedenberg and\nTroop Committeeman Reed Rowan.\nSeveral of the boys passed advance\nment and merit badge tests while\non the hike.\nA cash contribution was made by\nthe -boys to purchase young trees\nto be planted on the camp site.\nTransportation was furnished by C.\nBrickey, C. Bywaters, P. Creighton,\nS. Horvath, W. Shepler, and Scout\nmaster Louis Hackbarth.\nFeature of Wednesday night\u2019s\nregular meeting was the showing\noi technicolor films on First Aid\nand Yellowstone National Park\nshown by Paul McEnany with\nTroops Wy-8 and Wy-13 as guetss.\nRed Feather\nW orkers Begin\nSolicitation\nWith red-feather workers cover\ning every house, business, school,\nand industry, solicitation for the\nCommunity War Chest Campaign\nis well on its way, Harry Fenske,\nDownriver chairman, announced to\nday.\nIn Wyandotte. Kurt Breitfeld re\nports that the returns thus far re\nceived show that Wyandotte is do\ning its part to make the Downriver\ndrive a successful one.\nIf you think our own aged, sick\nand friendless deserve care and our\nown youth need recreational and\ncharacter-building activities, or\nphaned or neglected children need\nfoster homes\u2014if you think peoples\nof the formerly Axis-occupied coun\ntries deserve help if you think\nmembers of our armed forces de\nserve our hospitality, then you\u2019ll\nwant to give generously to the Com\nmunity War Chest. Your contribu\ntions become life-saving, morale\nbuilding assistance for people of\nyour own community and for people\nin need all over the world, Mr.\nBreitfeld said.\nOver 100 agencies are combined in\nthe united appeal for the Commun\nity War Chest. It is organized for\nefficient distribution of your help\nto the sick, the homeless, the\nfriendless, the orphans and the\nhungry, both here and abroad.\nYou may contribute to all the\nCommunity War Chest Agencies,\nthrough one donation or if you are\nparticularly interested in one or\nmore of the agencies, you may desi\ngnate that all or part of your sub\nscription be ear-marked for the work\nof those agencies.\nOpen your heart and purse wide\u2014\nand give generously to your Com\nmunity War Chest.\nMUCC Answers\nV nemploymen t\nBenefits Problems\nQ. How are the funds for unem\nployment compensation raised?\nA. Employers pay a percentage\nof their payroll into a State fund,\nand benefits are paid to eligible\nworkers from that fund. Employees\npay nothing toward unemployment\ncompensation.\nQ. Can I collect unemployment\ncompensation benefits when I am\nill and unable to w\u2019ork?\nA. No. The Michigan compen\nsation law provides that in order\nto be eligible for benefits, the un\nemployed person must be able to\nwork and available for full-time\nwork.\nQ. Suppose I register for work\nat the local employment office and\nfile my claim for unemployment\ncompensation. Then, after I have\nstarted to collect benefit checks, I\nfall ill. Can I continue to collect\nbenefits?\nA. No. In order to remain elig\nible for unemployment benefits,\nyou must be able to work during\nevery week for which you claim\nbenefits. If you are unable to work\nduring any week because of illness,\nor for any other reason, you are\nautomatically disqualified for ben\nefits for that week.\nQ. Where can I find out if I\nam eligible for unemployment com\npensation benefits?\nA. Inquire at the nearest office\nof the United States Employment\nService Michigan Unemployment\nCompensation Commission.\nQ. How do I apply for benefits?\nA. First you must register for\nwork at the nearest office of the\nUnited States Employment Service\n\u2014Michigan Unemployment Com\npensation Commission. Then file\nyqpr claim for unemployment ben\nefits in the same office.\nQ. What should I do when I file\nmy claim for benefits?\nA. You should be ready to give\nthe following information:\n1. Your name and addKss.\n2. Your Social Security Number.\n(Bring your Social Security Card\nwith you.)\n3. Your employer's name and ad\ndress.\n4. Your occupation.\n5. The date you became unem\nployed and the reason.\nIn addition, If you worked under\nany other name or Social Security\nnumber, be sure to mention It to\nyour local office.\nNapiwocki Cited\n*b.-\n5c,...\naB\nPfc. Edward Napiwocki\nPfc. Edward Napiwocki has been\ncited for meritorious performance\nof service with the 751st Tank bat\ntalion in Italy.\nPfc. Napiwocki entered the Army\non October 14, 1942 and trained at\nCamp Campbell, Kentucky. He\nsailed from New York, December 11,\n1942 and arrived in North Africa\nlater going to Italy. Napiwocki was\ncited for service during the period\nfrom October 1, 1943 to May 8, 1945\nwhen he participated in the Saler\nno and Anzio landings, Naples-\nFoggia, Rome-Amo, North Appe\nnine and Po Valley campaigns. He\nwas awarded the bronze service\narrowhead, Naples-Foggia, Rome-\nAmo, North Appennine and Po\nValley battle stars.\nPfc. Napiwcoki makes his home\nwith hLs brother, Frank Napiwocki\nat 231 Maple street.\nMcGee, Lewis Discharged\nS/Sgt. Edward J. McGee and Pfc.\nRoy A. Lewis have been discharged\nfrom the Armed forces this week.\nPfc. Lewis, son of Mrs. Belle\nLewis, 127 Bondie. received his re\nlease at Camp Breckinridge, Ken\ntucky. He was a member of the\nFifth Infantry division.\nMcGee, 22, son of Mr. and Mrs.\nEdward J. McGee, 413 Poplar street,\nwas discharged at the separation\nbase maintained at Santa Ana,\nCalifornia, by the Army Air Forces.\nSgt. McGee is a veteran of 32\nmonths of service in the AAF and\nserved in New Guinea and the East\nIndies with the 13th Air Force as a\nB-24 gunner for 11 months, com\npleting 40 combat missions.\nHe was awarded the Air Medal\nwith three Oak Leaf clusters. Be\nfore entering the service McGee\nwas employed by the Michigan\nBell Telephone company.\nBetween eight and ten news\npapers now are being published in\nthe part of Germany occupied by\nthe United States. Circulation\naverages more than 4.000,000 copies\nweekly.\nw vK\\\\ i\n52-Inches Wide Hand \u00ab*h\nScreened Cretonnes B I*P\nTwo distinctive patterns on rose, blue r\ngreen backgrounds.\n43-Inches Wide Hand g\nScreened Cretonnes I B*l\nGorgeous all-over patterns on tan. t -e. ggjp\nrose and green backgrounds.\nALL GUARANTEED\nWASHABLE\nCOLORS\nMarine Pvt. Messer mnme\nPvt. Gordon Messer, marine\ncorps, son of Mr. and Mrs. Charles\nMesser, Adams drive, Gibraltar,\narrived home Saturday from Parris\nIsland, South Carolina. Upon his\nreturn he will go to Maine. While\nhere he visited his grandparents,\nMr. and Mrs. Roy Daniels. Davis\nstreet, Wyandotte. Before his en\nlistment in July, Pvt. Messer was\nattending Trenton high school.\nWith each increase of one degree\nin temperature the speed of sound\nincreases about one foot per sec\nond, according to the Sonotone re\nsearch laboratories. At freezing (32\ndegrees) sound waves travel at 1087\nfeet per second, and at ordinary\nroom temperatures the velocity is\nabout 1130 feet per second. This\nis about 770 miles per hour.\nM\ntMRM\n\njL l\n/r ijlr\n9r r I Wi\nV\\\\ 1\nm\njsm\nf ir\nV i&AizJ\u00dfm\nI\n/I/IN I Wjt\n6\n\u25a0I JM irJ M\nml ml p\nj mj m i\nHI\" y\nj gvg? T-_ flp\n1 a pV\n1 1 n\n1 1\nSTORE HOURS: Monday thru Thursday, 9:30 to b P.M.\nFriday Saturday, 9:30 to 9 P.M.\nI ZUIEBACK'S\n3224 BIDDLE AVENUE\nvs\nJust Arrived!\nGORGEOUS\nCretonnes\nFOR LIVING ROOM AND DINING\nROOM DRAPERIES\nFOR BEDROOM ENSEMBLES\nFOR DECORATIVE PILLOWS\nRoughtex Cretonne\n54\u201d wide. Hand screen- jrsr m\ned Roughtex Cretonne. m\nTwo distinctive pat- \u20acLW\nterns on rose, blue and H\ngreen backgrounds. j Ui\u00bb JHL\niteleased From Service\nWilliam Wouczyna. residing *t\n647 Central, has been discharged\nfrom the Army at Fort Mver Sep\naration point. Fort Myer, Virginia.\nNATIONAL NURSES\nMEMORIAL PLANNED\nAmerica's war nurses of World\nWar 11, will be provided with a\nnational headquarters in Washine\nton to te known as the Nurses Na\ntional Memorial. A campaign to\nraise a minimum of $2,000,000 will\nbe launched to cover construction\ncosts.\nThe Nurses National Memorial\nwill be a completely equipped so\ncial center and temporary residence\nopen to all medical women of *he\nArmy, Navy and Air Corps.\nBuy Victory Bonds\nEye-catching button-fror.t\nclassic of a Cohama Fcbric\nlong sleeves and\nvraist-hugging belt.\nWith tricky ne*\nshirring to high-\nM waist front\nIf* ond beck end yoke,\nlinpressed front pleated skirt.\nIn junior sizes 9 to 17.\n10\u201d","height":"34572","width":"25890"}}
